## 4. Attachment policy

If Jira has attachments:

* list filenames when available
* do not guess screenshot/image/design content
* do not implement UI from unseen screenshots
* if MCP cannot inspect attachment content, ask the user to upload the needed file/image

Attachment metadata is not the same as understanding attachment content.

### 4.1 Attachment fallback — direct Jira API token

The Atlassian Rovo MCP server's OAuth scopes (`read_jira`, `read_confluence`, `search_jira`, etc.)
do not include attachment binary content. Calling `/rest/api/3/attachment/content/{id}` through
the MCP-issued token will return `403` even though the ticket itself is readable.

When this happens, do not stop at "ask user to upload." Try the API-token fallback first:

1. Check that `JIRA_API_TOKEN` and `JIRA_EMAIL` are set as environment variables
   (never read them from a hardcoded value, never print them, never write them to any file).
2. If both are present, fetch the attachment using Basic Auth instead of the MCP token:

```bash
   curl -s -u "${JIRA_EMAIL}:${JIRA_API_TOKEN}" \
     -o /tmp/<ticket-key>-<attachment-id>.png \
     -w "%{http_code}" \
     "https://uctalent.atlassian.net/rest/api/3/attachment/content/<attachment-id>"
```

3. Get `<attachment-id>` and filename from the MCP attachment metadata already fetched in
   Phase 1 (orchestrator) — do not guess the ID.
4. Save the downloaded file under `/tmp/` only. Never commit it, never move it into the repo.
5. If the HTTP status is `200`, read/view the downloaded image directly to understand the
   design before implementing UI.
6. If the HTTP status is still `403`/`401`, or `JIRA_API_TOKEN`/`JIRA_EMAIL` are not set,
   fall back to the existing rule: ask the user to upload the file/image manually. Do not
   attempt other workarounds, do not retry with different auth schemes, and do not guess
   content from the filename or metadata.

Never ask the user to paste their API token into chat. If the env vars are missing, tell the
user once which two variable names are needed and let them set up the token outside the
conversation.

This fallback applies to attachment content only. Ticket summary, description, comments, and
acceptance criteria continue to come from Jira MCP as the source of truth — do not switch the
whole ticket-fetch flow to the API token.

