## 5. Orchestrator rule

Use `orchestrator` as the default entrypoint for Jira tickets.

The orchestrator must:

1. fetch Jira through MCP
2. parse summary, description, AC, comments, attachments
3. read `docs/` when business logic is involved
4. use **Codegraph MCP** to explore symbols/files before delegating (§4.2)
5. route work to relevant repo(s)
6. decide parallel vs sequential execution
7. spawn focused subagents (pass `codegraph_hints`: symbols, files, call paths)
8. verify frontend/backend API contracts
9. call `testing` for backend and contract verification
10. aggregate the final report

Do not let implementation agents independently guess ticket scope.

The orchestrator owns scope, routing, contract alignment, and final reporting.

For fullstack tickets, the orchestrator may delegate to `fullstack-orchestrator` (`.cursor/agents/fullstack-orchestrator.md`).

### Skills and agents index

Load only what the ticket needs — do not read every skill/rule upfront.

| Work type | Skill | Rule(s) | Agent |
| --------- | ----- | ------- | ----- |
| Cross-repo Jira ticket | — | this file | `orchestrator` |
| Fullstack coordination | — | this file | `fullstack-orchestrator` |
| Verification | — | §9–10 below | `testing` |
| NestJS Backend V2 | `implement-backend` | `backend-architecture`, `backend-coding-standards`, `backend-project-architechture` | — |
| FastAPI | `implement-fastapi` | `backend-fastapi` | — |
| MUI frontend | `implement-frontend`, `mui-frontend` | `frontend-coding-standards` | — |
| Unchain Labs site | `implement-ucl-web` | `ucl-web-frontend` | — |
| Strapi CMS | `implement-strapi-cms` | `strapi-cms` | — |
| Domain / ownership | — | `domain-knowledge` + `docs/` | — |

All paths above are under `.cursor/`.

